I believe that "Distribution is Destiny"
The origin point is an empirical observation, not a theory. Watching Neuro-Sama, you noticed something the field mostly ignores: AI can be trained to have a personality. 
ChatGPT, Claude, Llama, Gemini they all feel distinctly different from each other, and that's not accidental. It's the residue of what each was trained on. Personality is
already being encoded whether you intend it or not. That's the seed of the thesis: the training distribution doesn't just teach the model what to know, it shapes who the model is.
Character is downstream of data. Not rules, not RLHF patches applied afterward, not runtime instructions. The model becomes whatever it was raised on for lack of a better word.
So the design question isn't "how do we align the model after training" it's "what kind of mind do we want, and what dees the Mind's world look like as a training distribution?"
Distribution is Destiny means alignment and capability aren't separate problems. If you build the distribution correctly, a misaligned model is pretty close to being not possible 
because there's no version of the reasoning patterns in training that contains misaligned thinking. It can only become what it trained on.

Reasoning
lets start with The 50/50 split. Good reasoning isn't all method and it isn't all freeform Chain of Thought. CoT alone is like a rough draft with lots of "oh wait I forgot,
let me reconsider" there's no discipline underneath it,just a stream of thoughts that happens to land somewhere. Pure formalized method without CoT just a sheet of paper.
What I'm after is the integration: is to formalize the structure of established reasoning traditions giving the skeleton, and the generative movement of CoT giving it breath.
The explicit half is what humans have codified like the Scientific Method, Five Whys, Socratic questioning, ECT. They are all fromalized Structure methods, Reasoning methods 
and Presentation methods its another kind of compound concept but it does have a English word to define it. These are standardized and can and should be made into CoT. 
Implicit reasoning is sililar but it just doesnt have the direct labbling of the reasoning steps and ridged it flows rather than plods. 

The philosophical stack I'm pointing at describes what it feels like when both halves are working together: The premise-to-conclusion engine running correctly
at each step thinking that moves through a problem rather than stumbling across/thorugh it 

What distinguishes this from the standard good reasoning is that it's clean, coherent, and has flow. There is no "oh wait or I fogot about xyz". 
Structure feeds reasoning, Reasoning feeds Presentation. A disconnected structure that doesn't actually constrain the reasoning isn't structure, it's decoration.

